      seoDescription:
        "<strong>Konjac Gum (E425i) and Konjac Glucomannan (E425ii)</strong> (CAS 37220-17-0) are high-molecular-weight, water-soluble glucomannan polysaccharides extracted from the corms of <em>Amorphophallus konjac</em> K. Koch. The raw konjac corm is dried and milled to produce konjac flour, which is further processed to produce refined Konjac Gum (E425i, ≥ 75% glucomannan) and high-purity Konjac Glucomannan (E425ii, ≥ 95% glucomannan). EFSA re-evaluated both forms in 2017 and confirmed safety at the maximum permitted level of 10 g/kg.<br><br>The glucomannan polysaccharide produces several commercially unique properties: the highest viscosity of any natural food gum (15,000–40,000 mPa·s at 1% for KGM E425ii), powerful synergistic gelation with kappa-carrageenan (forming firm, elastic, thermoreversible gels — a complete vegan substitute for gelatin), synergistic soft-gel formation with xanthan gum, and irreversible thermostable gel formation on alkali treatment (the basis of shirataki noodles and konnyaku cake).<br><br>In the <strong>food and beverage industry</strong>, Konjac Gum is used in konjac noodles (shirataki), konjac jelly products, vegan gelatin substitutes, plant-based dairy alternatives, low-calorie and reduced-fat foods, gluten-free bakery, beverages, and functional food formats. KGM carries two approved EU health claims: contribution to maintaining normal blood cholesterol levels (3 g/day) and contribution to weight management (1 g per meal, three times daily).<br><br>In <strong>pharmaceuticals</strong>, KGM is used as a dietary fibre supplement, sustained-release tablet matrix former, oral suspension viscosifier, and prebiotic gut health ingredient. In <strong>cosmetics and personal care</strong>, KGM is used in facial sheet masks, moisturisers, serums, hair care products, konjac sponges, and toothpaste.<br><br><strong>VIVINE International</strong> supplies Konjac Gum (E425i) and Konjac Glucomannan (E425ii) in food grade, pharmaceutical-quality, and cosmetic grade with full TDS, SDS, and COA documentation.",
